    "name": "GOES16-L2-GLM",
    "title": "GOES-16 Lightning Detection",
    "description": "The Geostationary Lightning Mapper (GLM) is a single-channel, near-infrared optical transient detector capable of identifying brief changes in the optical scene that signal the presence of lightning. It continuously monitors total lightning across the Americas and adjacent ocean regions, maintaining a nearly uniform spatial resolution of approximately 10 km (8 km nadir, 14 km edge fov). The data are the original GLM products received and generated by the GOES-R reception station operated by INPE (National Institute for Space Research) in Brazil. GLM collects key information such as the frequency, location, and spatial extent of lightning activity, which supports the detection of strengthening thunderstorms and tropical cyclones. Trends in total lightning observed by GLM provide crucial guidance to forecasters, enabling earlier identification of severe storms before they produce damaging winds, hail, or even tornadoes. The GLM data product is organized into a hierarchy of earth-located lightning radiant energy measurements consisting of events, groups, and flashes: Events are individual lightning detections made by the instrument; Groups consist of one or more events that meet predefined spatial and temporal coincidence criteria; Flashes are composed of one or more groups that also satisfy spatial and temporal thresholds. This product includes the relationships between events, groups, and flashes, along with the spatial coverage of groups and flashes. It also contains metadata related to data processing, quality assurance, and satellite position and status.",
